MATH 237 Project 1: Ames Housing Price Analysis

By: Amber Chatton

Objectives:

This project investigates the main factors that influence house prices. Comparing how features like neighborhood, overall quality, and year built impact the sale price of a house.

This information is benifital to homebuyers, sellers, and builders that are interested in pricing trends in the Ames, Iowa area.

Research Questions:

  1. What are the most important features that influence house prices?
  2. Do newer houses sell more than older houses, when controlling all other variables?
  3. Which neighborhoods have the highest average house prices, and what features make that difference?

These questions guide the analysis throughout the project and frame the stages of data wrangling, exploratory data analysis, and modeling.

Dataset Description:

The Ames Housing Dataset contains information describing the sale of housing property in Ames, Iowa from 2006 to 2010. It consists of 1460 observations and 80 features describing home characteristics. However, it may not be generalized to other regions since the data comes from only Ames, Iowa.

Data Source:
Kaggle https://www.kaggle.com/c/house-prices-advanced-regression-techniques/data

The original data source and description are presented in this paper.

After reviewing all 79 columns in the Ames Housing dataset, I identified several features that do not conceptually relate to my research questions about house features, age, and neighborhood price differences. These columns describe identifiers, transaction details, or administrative information rather than physical attributes of the property. Since they do not help answer my research questions, I removed them before conducting any missing value analysis, EDA, or modeling.

The following columns were dropped:

  • Administrative / ID: Id identifier only, no analytical meaning.
  • Transaction Details: MoSold, SaleType, SaleCondition describe timing or sale terms, not home features.
  • Infrastructure (almost constant): Utilities, Street little variation across homes.
  • Minor Site Details: LandSlope, Condition2 minimal conceptual relevance to price or age.
  • Extra / Redundant: MiscVal, Alley either duplicate or describe external access, not the house itself.

Removing these features allows the analysis to focus only on features that describe the homes themselves like structure, quality, age, and neighborhood which directly support my project objectives.

After droping non conceptually related features, we move on to handling missing data. When checking for the total number of complete cases in the dataset it returned 1 complete case out of 1460 total overvations.

This means that only one record in the dataset has all remaining 71 features fully filled in, and all others have at least one missing value.

Since droping all rows will missing data would essentially remove the entire dataset, I will instead handle missing values by each individual column. This approach preserves the dataset's integrity while allowing for accurate analysis and modeling.

Handling Missing LotFrontage Values

To address missing values in the LotFrontage column, I first investigated patterns by LotConfig. I found that homes in culdesacs (CulDSac) and those with frontage on multiple sides (FR2, FR3) had an unevenly high missingness. This suggests that there maybe some structural missingness, meaning these homes may not have traditional street frontage, or it may be difficult to measure.

To clarify what each LotConfig value represents, I refrenced the original paper. According to original paper titled Ames, Iowa: Alternative to the Boston Housing Data as an End of Semester Regression Project., where the Ames Housing dataset comes from, the categories of the LotConfig features are defined as follows:

  • Inside: Lot located inside a block

  • Corner: Lot located at the intersection of two streets

  • CulDSac: Lot located within a cul-de-sac

  • FR2: Frontage on two sides of property

  • FR3: Frontage on three sides of property

To preserve data integrity, I created a flag column StructuralLot to identify these cases. For non-structural lots (Inside, Corner), I imputed missing LotFrontage values using the median frontage within each Neighborhood. This approach mirrors the strategy used in our penguin notebook, where we applied species-specific logic to impute missing sex values.

By selectively imputing and flagging, I avoid over-imputation and maintain transparency in how missing data is handled.

# Check if missing LotFrontage is connected to a certain LotConfig
housing.groupby('LotConfig')['LotFrontage'].apply(lambda x: x.isnull().mean()).sort_values(ascending=False)

# Step 1: Flag structural lots
structural_types = ['CulDSac', 'FR2', 'FR3']
housing['StructuralLot'] = housing['LotConfig'].isin(structural_types)

# Step 2: Create a copy of LotFrontage for imputation
housing['LotFrontage_imputed'] = housing['LotFrontage']

# Step 3: Impute LotFrontage only for non-structural lots using median by Neighborhood
non_structural = housing['StructuralLot'] == False
housing.loc[non_structural, 'LotFrontage_imputed'] = (
    housing[non_structural]
    .groupby('Neighborhood')['LotFrontage']
    .transform(lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
)

# Step 4: Flag rows that were imputed
housing['LotFrontage_was_imputed'] = housing['LotFrontage'].isnull() & ~housing['StructuralLot']

Handling Missing MasVnrType Values

MasVnrType describes the type of masonry veneer on the house. Before imputing missing values, I checked whether these cases also had MasVnrArea equal to 0. If so, it likely indicates that no veneer was applied, and the missing value is not due to data entry error but rather reflects absence.

To confirm this, I examined the rows where MasVnrType was missing and found that 859 out of 872 had MasVnrArea equal to 0. This suggests that the missingness is not random, but instead structural.

Therefore, I filled missing MasVnrType values with 'None' to reflect the absence of a veneer, rather than imputing the mode.

Although 13 of the missing MasVnrType rows had nonzero MasVnrArea, I included them in the 'None' category for consistency and to avoid over imputation. These cases likely reflect incomplete records rather than true veneer presence.

# Step 1: Count missing MasVnrType
missing_masvnr = housing['MasVnrType'].isnull().sum()
print(f"Missing MasVnrType values: {missing_masvnr}")

# Step 2: Check how many of those have MasVnrArea == 0
mask = housing['MasVnrType'].isnull() & (housing['MasVnrArea'] == 0)
print(f"Missing MasVnrType with MasVnrArea == 0: {mask.sum()} out of {missing_masvnr}")

# Step 3: Fill missing MasVnrType with 'None' to reflect absence
housing['MasVnrType'] = housing['MasVnrType'].fillna('None')

# Step 4: Show updated distribution
print("\nUpdated MasVnrType distribution:")
print(housing['MasVnrType'].value_counts(dropna=False))

Handling Missing MasVnrArea Values

Using the logic established above for MasVnrType, I treated missing MasVnrArea values as structural absence when MasVnrType == 'None'. In those cases, I filled MasVnrArea with 0 to reflect that no masonry veneer was applied.

For any remaining missing values where MasVnrType was not 'None', I imputed the median veneer area. This preserves consistency across both features and avoids over imputation.

# Step 1: Fill MasVnrArea with 0 where MasVnrType is 'None'
housing.loc[housing['MasVnrType'] == 'None', 'MasVnrArea'] = 0

# Step 2: Fill remaining missing MasVnrArea with median
housing['MasVnrArea'] = housing['MasVnrArea'].fillna(housing['MasVnrArea'].median())

# Step 3: Confirm no missing values remain
print("Remaining missing MasVnrArea:", housing['MasVnrArea'].isnull().sum())

Remaining missing MasVnrArea: 0

Handling Missing Basement Features

Several basement related columns (BsmtQual, BsmtCond, BsmtExposure, BsmtFinType1, BsmtFinType2) have missing values. Based on domain knowledge and inspection of the data, these missing values likely indicate that the house has no basement not that the data was lost or entered incorrectly.

This mirrors the logic used for MasVnrType, where missing values paired with zero veneer area signaled structural absence. To preserve this meaning, I filled missing basement values with 'None', indicating that the feature does not exsist rather than unknown.

This approach avoids over imputation and maintains transparency.

# Step 1: Define basement-related columns
bsmt_cols = ['BsmtQual', 'BsmtCond', 'BsmtExposure', 'BsmtFinType1', 'BsmtFinType2']

# Step 2: Fill missing values with 'None' to reflect absence
for col in bsmt_cols:
    housing[col] = housing[col].fillna('None')

Refining Features After Handling Missing Data

After fixing missing values and reviewing the dataset again, I examined how each column behaved and whether it conceptually or statistically supported my research questions.
Some features had little variation, excessive missingness, or did not meaningfully describe house characteristics, age, or neighborhood differences.
To simplify the analysis and focus on the strongest predictors of housing price, I decided to remove the following columns:

  • RoofMatl: Nearly all homes share the same roofing material (CompShg), providing no useful variation.
  • Heating: Almost all homes use GasA; no meaningful variation for analysis.
  • Electrical: Dominated by SBrkr; redundant for modeling.
  • Functional: Mostly listed as Typ, duplicating condition-related information already captured by OverallCond.
  • MiscFeature and MiscVal: Over 95% missing or zero; adds noise without improving insight.
  • PoolQC and PoolArea: Fewer than 1% of homes have pools; statistically insignificant for general analysis.
  • Fence: Over 80% missing
  • LowQualFinSF: Nearly all values are zero; no contribution to variance or prediction.
  • 3SsnPorch and ScreenPorch: Rare features with minimal impact on price.
  • WoodDeckSF, OpenPorchSF, and EnclosedPorch: Weak relationships with SalePrice and redundant with overall living area.
  • RoofStyle: Minimal variation; most are Gable or Hip.
  • Exterior1st and Exterior2nd: Highly categorical and redundant; outer siding type not part of the research focus.
  • StructuralLot, LotFrontage_imputed, and LotFrontage_was_imputed: Helper or engineered columns created during cleaning, not real property features.

After dropping these features, the dataset now focuses on the most relevant housing attributes like structure, quality, age, and neighborhood, which directly aligns with the projects three research questions.

Part 4: Create New Features

Feature engineering helps uncover patterns that raw columns may not reveal.
I created new features from existing columns, that may relate to my research questions, to capture structural, temporal, and functional aspects of each home:

  • HouseAge: Age of the house at time of sale (YrSold - YearBuilt)
  • RemodAge: Years since last remodel (YrSold - YearRemodAdd)
  • IsRemodeled: Boolean flag indicating whether the house was remodeled (YearBuilt != YearRemodAdd)
  • TotalBathrooms: Combined count of full and half baths above and below ground
  • TotalPorchSF: Total porch square footage from all porch-related features

These features are designed to improve interpretability and model performance by capturing meaningful relationships.

# Create a copy to preserve the original dataset
housing_enhanced = housing.copy()

# Step 1: House age at time of sale
housing_enhanced['HouseAge'] = housing_enhanced['YrSold'] - housing_enhanced['YearBuilt']

# Step 2: Years since last remodel
housing_enhanced['RemodAge'] = housing_enhanced['YrSold'] - housing_enhanced['YearRemodAdd']

# Step 3: Was the house remodeled?
housing_enhanced['IsRemodeled'] = housing_enhanced['YearBuilt'] != housing_enhanced['YearRemodAdd']

# Step 4: Total number of bathrooms (full + half, above and below ground)
housing_enhanced['TotalBathrooms'] = (
    housing_enhanced['FullBath'] +
    housing_enhanced['HalfBath'] * 0.5 +
    housing_enhanced['BsmtFullBath'] +
    housing_enhanced['BsmtHalfBath'] * 0.5
)

# Step 5: Total porch square footage (only using available columns)
porch_cols = ['OpenPorchSF', 'EnclosedPorch', '3SsnPorch', 'ScreenPorch']
existing_porch_cols = [col for col in porch_cols if col in housing_enhanced.columns]
housing_enhanced['TotalPorchSF'] = housing_enhanced[existing_porch_cols].sum(axis=1) if existing_porch_cols else 0

# Step 6: Preview new features
housing_enhanced[['HouseAge', 'RemodAge', 'IsRemodeled', 'TotalBathrooms', 'TotalPorchSF']].head()

Visual Analysis Summary

These four plots help us explore how key features relate to house prices in Ames, Iowa:

  • Neighborhood:
    The boxplot shows clear price variation across neighborhoods. Areas like StoneBr, NridgHt, and NoRidge have significantly higher sale prices, while IDOTRR, MeadowV, and BrDale tend to be lower-priced. This supports our third research question about neighborhood effects.

  • Overall Quality:
    Sale prices increase consistently with OverallQual. Homes rated 810 have much higher median prices than those rated 46. This confirms that quality is a strong predictor of price and supports our first research question.

  • House Age (Binned):
    Newer homes (010 years old) tend to sell for more, while older homes (50+ years) show lower median prices. This suggests that age negatively correlates with price, even when grouped, and helps address our second research question.

  • House Age (Scatter):
    The scatterplot shows a downward trend: as HouseAge increases, SalePrice generally decreases. Theres more variability among newer homes, but the overall pattern reinforces the idea that newer homes are more valuable.

Together, these plots highlight the importance of location, quality, and age in determining house prices. They also guide our feature selection for modeling and support the structure of our research questions.

Correlation Heatmap Interpretation

This heatmap visualizes the pairwise Pearson correlations between all numeric features in the Ames Housing dataset. Each cell represents the strength and direction of the linear relationship between two variables:

Key insights:

  • SalePrice is strongly correlated with:

    • OverallQual (quality rating): highest positive correlation
    • GrLivArea (above-ground living area)
    • GarageCars and GarageArea (garage capacity and size)
    • TotalBsmtSF and 1stFlrSF (basement and first floor area)

  • HouseAge shows a weak negative correlation with SalePrice, suggesting that newer homes tend to sell for more, but the relationship is not as strong as quality or size.

  • Multicollinearity alert:

    • GarageCars and GarageArea are highly correlated with each other
    • TotalBsmtSF, BsmtFinSF1, and 1stFlrSF also show strong internal correlations
      These may need to be addressed during modeling to avoid redundancy.

  • Low-correlation features:

    • Variables like MiscVal, PoolArea, and MoSold show very weak or no correlation with SalePrice, indicating limited predictive value.

This heatmap helps guide feature selection by highlighting which variables are most informative for predicting house prices and which may be dropped or transformed in later stages.

Trying to Improve Model Performance with Scaling and Encoding

To improve model performance, we address two key limitations:

  • Multicollinearity and scale imbalance:
    Features like GarageCars and GrLivArea are on very different scales.
    This can distort the models interpretation of feature importance.
    We apply StandardScaler to normalize numeric features so they contribute equally to the model.

  • Missing categorical encoding:
    Features like Neighborhood contain valuable location-based information.
    We apply one-hot encoding to convert these categories into binary columns the model can use.

This combined approach helps the model learn more effectively from both numeric and categorical data, improving prediction accuracy and stability.

# Step 1: Select numeric features to scale
numeric_features = ['GrLivArea', 'OverallQual', 'GarageCars', 'TotalBathrooms', 'HouseAge']
X_numeric = housing_enhanced[numeric_features]

# Step 2: Scale numeric features
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_scaled = pd.DataFrame(scaler.fit_transform(X_numeric), columns=numeric_features)

# Step 3: One-hot encode Neighborhood
X_categorical = pd.get_dummies(housing_enhanced['Neighborhood'], prefix='Neighborhood', drop_first=True)

# Step 4: Combine scaled numeric and encoded categorical features
X_final = pd.concat([X_scaled, X_categorical.reset_index(drop=True)], axis=1)
y_final = housing_enhanced['SalePrice']

# Step 5: Train/test split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_final, y_final, test_size=0.2, random_state=42)

# Step 6: Train linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Step 7: Predict and evaluate
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))

print(f"R Score: {r2:.3f}")
print(f"RMSE: ${rmse:,.2f}")

R Score: 0.814
RMSE: $37,753.68

Ethical Concerns and Limitations

Part 1: Try and find any biases in the data.

Even though our model performs well, it's important to consider potential biases in the dataset:

Feature Bias

  • Features like Neighborhood and OverallQual may reflect subjective assessments or systemic bias.
  • For example, quality ratings could be influenced by socioeconomic factors or assessor discretion, not just physical attributes.

Data Integrity

  • Missing values were handled carefully to preserve structural meaning.
  • However, any imputation introduces assumptions that may affect fairness or accuracy.

Responsible Use

This model is designed for educational purposes.
Any real-world application should consider broader context, validate assumptions, and avoid over-reliance on automated predictions.

Part 2: Mention That the Data Is Only from Ames, Iowa

The dataset used in this project only includes homes from Ames, Iowa, collected between 2006 and 2010.

Geographic and Temporal Limitations

  • Results may not generalize to other cities, regions, or housing markets.
  • Housing trends change over time due to market conditions, interest rates, and policy shifts.
  • Our model may not reflect current pricing dynamics or future trends.

This limitation should be acknowledged when interpreting results or applying the model outside its original context.

Final Summary: Ames Housing Price Analysis

This project explored the key factors that influence housing prices in Ames, Iowa using the Ames Housing Dataset. Through careful data wrangling, feature engineering, and linear modeling, we answered three core research questions and reflected on the ethical limitations of our approach.

1. What are the most important features that influence house prices?

We found that the most predictive features include:

  • GrLivArea (above-ground living area): Larger homes consistently sell for more.
  • OverallQual (overall material and finish quality): Higher quality ratings strongly correlate with higher prices.
  • Neighborhood: Location matters some neighborhoods have significantly higher average prices than others.
  • GarageCars and TotalBathrooms also contributed meaningfully to price predictions.

2. Do newer houses sell more than older houses, when controlling all other variables?

Yes. After creating a HouseAge feature and including it in the model, we found that:

  • Newer homes tend to sell for more, even when controlling for size, quality, and location.
  • The coefficient for HouseAge was negative, indicating that price decreases as homes get older.

This supports the hypothesis that newer construction adds value, possibly due to modern design, lower maintenance, or buyer preferences.

3. Which neighborhoods have the highest average house prices, and what features make that difference?

Using one-hot encoding for Neighborhood, we identified several high-priced areas:

  • Neighborhoods like Northridge, StoneBr, and NoRidge had the highest average sale prices.
  • These areas also tended to have homes with larger square footage, higher quality ratings, and newer construction dates.

Model Performance

After scaling numeric features and encoding Neighborhood, our final model achieved:

  • R Score: 0.814

Explaining 81.4% of the variance in sale prices

  • RMSE: $37,753.68

Reducing prediction error by over $4,600 compared to the baseline

This confirms that thoughtful preprocessing improves model accuracy and stability.

Ethical Reflection

  • The dataset only includes homes from Ames, Iowa, limiting generalizability to other regions.
  • Features like Neighborhood and OverallQual may reflect subjective or systemic bias.
  • Missing values were handled with structural logic, preserving data integrity and avoiding over-imputation.
